<head ><bibl  n='urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0014.tlg014' type='cts-urn'>Dem. 14</bibl></head>
<p >(<name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>, <title >On the Navy-Boards</title>; see also <name  n='oratory' type='ancientGenre'>Oratory</name>). In <date  when='-0354'>354 BCE</date>, a topic of debate in the Athenian <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term> was whether or not to go to war against <placeName  key='Persia'>Persia</placeName>. <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> had recently settled a war, the so-called <soCalled >Social War</soCalled>, in which <placeName  key='Rhodes'>Rhodes</placeName>, <placeName  key='Cos'>Cos</placeName>, and <placeName  key='Chios'>Chios</placeName> revolted against Athenian control. During this war, rumors came to <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> that <placeName  key='Persia'>Persia</placeName> was making naval preparations. This news caused a great deal of concern, and led to talk of a Greek alliance, organized by <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName>, waging war against <placeName  key='Persia'>Persia</placeName>. This speech, <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name>’ first speech before the <term  sortKey='Assembly'>Assembly</term>, argues against an immediate declaration of war, but proposes a program of military preparation. His particular suggestion was a reform of the <term  sortKey='Money'>trierarchy</term>, the means by which individual Athenians (or small groups of citizens) undertook the maintance of a warship on the city’s behalf (see the article on <term  sortKey='Liturgies'>Liturgies</term>). <placeName  key='Athens'>Athens</placeName> did not declare war on <placeName  key='Persia'>Persia</placeName>, but did not adopt <name  type='ancientAuthor'>Demosthenes</name> ’ suggestions either. (Source: <bibl >J.H. Vince, <title >Demosthenes I</title> [Cambridge, Mass.; Loeb Classical Library; 1930] 380-81</bibl>). </p>
<byline >Christopher Blackwell</byline>
